title.narrative: NUTRITION IN EMERGENCY

description.narrative: Government and other partners have increased capacity at the national and sub-national levels for humanitarian coordination and delivery of quality nutrition services, and emergency services are delivered, in line with the CCCs and international standards., which contributes to Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition, Supply And Logistics. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Partnerships And Engagement: Public And Private, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: NUTRITION Outcome: Improved coverage and increased utilization of quality and equitable nutrition services for under five children, adolescent girls and mothers in most deprived provinces and areas.

description.narrative: A total of 320,523;(143,074 boys & 177,449 girls) children aged under-five were provided with Severe Acute Malnutrition (SAM treatment services against the target of 400,000 children;through;more than 1,400;BPHS facilities and;around 120 mobile teams.;Similarly, a total of 92,223 children aged 6-59 months were provided with Vitamin A supplementation and Deworming. Furthermore, 67,456;pregnant and lactating women were provided with Infant and;Young;child Feeding (IYCF-E) services | Status:On-track | As-of Date:12/01/2022
